rately transgressed moral and ethical norms, or who even targeted themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aCrime in literature. 0aDeviant behavior in literature. 0aJustice in literature. 0aLiterature, EuropeanyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 0aPunishment in literature. 0aSocial control in literature. 0aSocial norms in literature. 4aMittelalter /Literatur. 4aMittelalter/ Recht. 4aStrafe. 4aVerbrechen. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCrime.  aMedieval Culture.  aMedieval Law.  aMedieval Literature.  aPunishment.1 aBeusterien, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBjaï, Denis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClason, Christopher R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClassen, Albrecht, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClassen, Albrecht, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCoudert, Allison P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGough, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHahn, Stacey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJost, Jean E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomornicka, Jolanta N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLlewellyn, Kathleen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLombart, Nicolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuef, Evelyne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoffitt Peacock, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiiranen, 